13 he said to us as we were near it;
14 because of which I became, when I heard it,
15 like one who is put in the grave.

19 My kind guides turned to me;
20 and Virgil said to me: “My son,
21 here there can be torment, but not death.

31 Now lay down, lay down all fear;
32 turn here and come: enter safely!”.
33 And I stood still, against my conscience.

37 As Pyramus, at the name of Thisbe, opened his eyes
38 upon death and looked at her,
39 at the moment when the mulberry tree turned red;

61 “The sun is going down”, he added, “and evening is coming;
62 do not stop, but quicken your pace,
63 while the west does not grow dark”.

73 each of us made a bed of a step;
74 for the nature of the mountain deprived us
75 of the power and the pleasure to climb further.

79 silent in the shade, while the sun is scorching,
80 watched by the shepherd, who has leaned on his crook
81 and is keeping watch over them as they rest;

82 and as the herdsman who lodges outdoors
83 spends the quiet night beside his flock,
84 watching so that no wild beast may scatter it;

88 Little of the daylight could appear there;
89 but, through that little, I saw the stars
90 brighter and larger than their wont.

103 To please myself in the mirror, I adorn myself here;
104 but my sister Rachel never moves away
105 from her looking-glass, and sits there all day.

106 She is as eager to see her beautiful eyes
107 as I am to adorn myself with my hands;
108 seeing satisfies her, and working satisfies me”.

